<target_code>
Here is the code of OS_CondVarUnlock_Impl:
```c
int32 OS_CondVarUnlock_Impl(const OS_object_token_t *token)
{
    int                                status;
    OS_impl_condvar_internal_record_t *impl;

    impl = OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET(OS_impl_condvar_table, *token);

    status = pthread_mutex_unlock(&impl->mut);
    if (status != 0)
    {
        return OS_ERROR;
    }

    return OS_SUCCESS;
}
```
</target_code>

    pthread_cond_t  cv;
} OS_impl_condvar_internal_record_t
...

{
    return token->obj_idx;
}
</additional code>

explanation: I inspected the entire provided code (OS_CondVarUnlock_Impl function body and the related type/array definitions). None of the fragments contain any call to memcmp, strcmp, strncmp, or any other string comparison of null-terminated strings. The function only calls pthread_mutex_unlock(&impl->mut) and returns OS_SUCCESS/OS_ERROR. The related definitions show an array of OS_impl_condvar_internal_record_t and that the record contains pthread types (pthread_mutex_t and pthread_cond_t) — no character arrays or string operations are present. The inline helper OS_ObjectIndexFromToken simply returns token->obj_idx (no string comparison). Therefore there are no occurrences of memcmp used to compare null-terminated strings in the provided code. (If OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET or the full definition of OS_object_token_t are defined elsewhere, those definitions would need to be checked, but they are not part of the supplied code.)
